==College career==
Turner attended [[LSU Tigers football|Louisiana State University]] (LSU) from 2011 to 2013. After redshirting as a freshman in 2011, he played in 12 games and made seven starts as a redshirt freshman.<ref name="LSU bio">http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=205087847</ref> He made his first start at right guard in a win over number 3 ranked [[University of South Carolina|South Carolina]].<ref name="LSU bio"/> In 559 snaps, Turner finished 2nd on the team with 51 pancake blocks.<ref name="LSU bio"/> LSU had a 100-yard rusher from four of the seven games in which Turner started. In his redshirt sophomore year, Turner started and played in all 13 games. In 857 snaps, he recorded 64 pancake blocks and in his final collegiate game at the [[2014 Outback Bowl]], Turner registered a season-high 10 pancake blocks and helped pave the way for 220 rushing yards against Iowa in a win.<ref name="LSU bio"/> For his career, Turner played a total of 1,416 snaps with 115 pancake blocks.<ref name="LSU bio"/>

He opted to forgo final two years of eligibility at LSU and entered into the [[2014 NFL Draft]] after his sophomore season.<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000312779/article/lsu-ol-trai-turner-intends-to-enter-nfl-draft LSU OL Trai Turner intends to enter NFL draft]</ref><ref>[http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2014/01/lsu_guard_trai_turner_leavingg.html LSU guard Trai Turner leaving Tigers for NFL draft]</ref>

==Professional career==
Turner surprised many with his decision to enter the [[2014 NFL Draft]] as he only had 20 career college starts.<ref>[http://www.rotoworld.com/recent/cfb/131813/trai-turner Trai Turner Rotoworld College Player Page]</ref> While he was highly regarded within NFL draft circles, many believed that by spending another year in school, Turner could have solidified himself as a first round draft pick in the [[2015 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Day Two Analysis: Kony Ealy And Trai Turner|url=http://www.thecharlottesportsblog.com/panthers/day-two-analysis-kony-ealy-and-trai-turner|website=TheCharlotteSportsBlog.com|date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> His power as a run blocker, mean streak, and length drew comparisons to [[Marshal Yanda]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 NFL Draft Scouting Report – Trai Turner, G LSU|url=http://withthefirstpick.com/2014/03/31/2014-nfl-draft-scouting-report-trai-turner-g-lsu/|website=WithTheFirstPick.com}}</ref> At the 2014 NFL combine, Turner surprised many analysts with his speed and athleticism, recording the fastest 40-yard dash among offensive guards.<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/combine/top-performers#year=2014&workout=FORTY_YARD_DASH&position=OL OL 40 Yard Dash Top Performers - 2014 NFL Combine]</ref> [[Dallas Cowboys]] executive vice president [[Stephen Jones (Dallas Cowboys)|Stephen Jones]] noted after the [[2014 NFL Draft]] that had the Cowboys not traded the number 78 overall selection in a deal to move up to select Boise State defensive end [[DeMarcus Lawrence]], they would have used that pick to draft Turner, whom they regarded as an immediate starter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cowboys VP: We likely would have drafted Ealy absent trade|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000350323/article/cowboys-vp-we-likely-would-have-drafted-ealy-absent-trade|author=Goodbread, Chase|website=NFL.com|date=May 14, 2014}}</ref>

Turner was drafted by the [[Carolina Panthers]] in the third round (92nd overall) of the [[2014 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Panthers draft G Turner in third round|url=http://www.panthers.com/news/article-2/Panthers-draft-G-Turner-in-third-round/3414d084-35fa-4828-a2b8-82ff8470b668|author=Henson, Max|website=Panthers.com|date=May 9, 2014|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref>

